We first identify the Cash Flow from Operating Activities from the cash flow statement (which is –6,856,840.58) and then identify total debt from the balance sheet. Since the liabilities in these examples consist solely of current liabilities (Accounts Payable and Taxes Payable), we add these up:

• Accounts Payable = 1,260,000.00  
• Taxes Payable = 341,835.08  
• Total Debt = 1,260,000.00 + 341,835.08 = 1,601,835.08

Next, the Cash Flow to Debt Ratio is calculated as:  
  Ratio = (Cash Flow from Operating Activities) / (Total Debt)  
    = –6,856,840.58 / 1,601,835.08  
    ≈ –4.28

Thus, the Cash Flow to Debt Ratio is approximately –4.28.
